      "SummaryText": "Risk Management Plan (RMP) - Ammonia\n\nExecutive Summary\n\nBleigh Farms Inc. \n\nPalmyra , Missouri         \n\n\n\n\n\n1. Accidental Release Prevention and Emergency Response Policies\n\nWe at Bleigh Farms Inc. in Palmyra, Missouri are strongly committed to employee, public, and environmental safety.  This \n\ncommitment is an inherent part of our comprehensive accidental release prevention program that covers areas such as design, installation, operating procedures, maintenance, and employee training associated with the processes at our facility.  It is our policy to implement appropriate controls to prevent possible releases of regulated substances.  We coordinate our response efforts with the Palmyra Fire Department and Marion County Local Emergency Planning Committee, \n\nwhich provides additional emergency response expertise.\n\n\n\n2. Stationary Source and Regulated Substances Handled\n\nOur facility's primary activities include support services for crop production.  We have anhydrous ammonia stored in one 30,000-gallon tank and two 6,000 gallon interconnected tanks and seven 1,000-gallon nurse tanks at our facility in Hannibal, Missouri. The maximum amount stored is 49,000 gallons ( 214,331 pounds) including the capacity of  the on-site nurse tanks.   The largest single storage vessel at our facility contains 131,220 pounds at  85% standard maximum storage capacity.\n\n\n\n3. Worst Case Release and Alternative Release Scenarios (NOTE: This information is for LEPC, Fire Department and Bleigh Farms Inc. incident planning use.  These paragraphs were deleted from the Executive Summary sent to the EPA.)\n\n\n\n4. General Accidental Release Prevention Program\n\nOur facility has taken all the necessary steps to comply with the EPA's accidental release prevention requirements as set forth in 40 CFR part 68.  The following sections briefly describe the elements of the release prevention program that is in place at our stationary source.\n\n\n\nProcess Safety Information\n\nBleigh Farms, Inc. maintains a"
    },
